\left( {\\epsilon }_{ - } + 2V\\cos k\\right) }^{2}}{{\\epsilon }_{ - }^{2}{\\left( {\\epsilon }_{ - } + 2V\\cos k\\right) }^{2} + 4{V}^{4}{\\sin }^{2}k} \\tag{3}\\]\n\nfor the reflection probability. The reflection coefficient vanishes then when \\( {\\epsilon }_{a} - {\\epsilon }_{b} =  - {2V}\\cos k \\) or equivalently when \\( - {2V} \\leq  {\\epsilon }_{a} - {\\epsilon }_{b} \\leq  {2V} \\) . We point out that when this condition holds,or equivalently when \\( E\\left( k\\right)  = {\\epsilon }_{b} \\) ,the product of a pair of \\( b \\) transfer matrices yields the unit matrix. Under such conditions, Furstenberg's theorem implies that the electronic state at that energy will be extended. \\( {}^{6} \\) The location in the parent-ordered band of the perfectly transmitted electronic state corresponds to the wave vector \\( {k}_{0} = {\\cos }^{-1}\\left\\lbrack  {\\left( {{\\epsilon }_{b} - {\\epsilon }_{a}}\\right) /{2V}}\\right\\rbrack \\) . Of course,no transport would occur if only a single electronic state remained unscattered. To determine the total number of states that behave in this fashion,we expand \\( R \\) around \\( {k}_{0} \\) . To lowest order we find that in the vicinity of \\( {k}_{0} \\) , \\( {\\left| R\\right| }^{2} \\sim  {\\left( \\Delta k\\right) }^{2} \\) where \\( {\\Delta k} = k - {k}_{0} \\) . Consider now a crystal containing a certain fraction of randomly placed dimer impurities. Electronic states in the vicinity of \\( {k}_{0} \\) will be reflected with a probability proportional to \\( {\\left( \\Delta k\\right) }^{2} \\) . The time between scattering events \\( \\tau \\) is inversely proportional to the reflection probability. \\( {}^{7} \\) As a result,in the random system,the mean free path \\( \\lambda  = \\langle v\\rangle \\tau  \\sim  1/{\\left( \\Delta k\\right) }^{2} \\) in the vicinity of \\( {k}_{0} \\) ,where \\( v \\) is the velocity. \\( {}^{7} \\) Let \\( {\\Delta k} \\) \\( = {\\Delta N}/{2\\pi N} \\) . Upon equatin